{
  "explanation": "A butterfly spread is a neutral, limited-risk, limited-profit options strategy. An investor purchases a butterfly spread when they anticipate that the price of the underlying asset will experience very little volatility over the life of the options. The strategy is structured to achieve its maximum profit if the underlying asset's price is exactly equal to the middle strike price at expiration. The profit diminishes as the price moves away from this central point, and the position results in a loss if the price moves too far in either direction (below the lowest strike or above the highest strike). Therefore, it is a bet on price stability and is unsuitable for an investor expecting large price swings (high volatility) or a strong directional move.",
  "conclusion": "The strategy is most appropriate when the price of the underlying stock is expected to stay close to the central strike price."
}
